1 Creating a Scatterplot of Penguin Bill Length vs Flipper Length

From size measurements for adult foraging penguins near Palmer Station, Antarctica, we wish to display a relationship between their bill and flipper lengths for a sample of the penguin species.

For each of the three species in the first graph, there is a significant moderate positive linear relationship between a penguins bill length and flipper length. Hence, as a penguins bill length increases, the length of its flipper tends to increase as well. However, for the Adelie species, there is a weaker relationship than for the other species (since the points are more spread out making it harder to see the positive relationship). From the scatterplot, we can also see that, on average, a Gentoo and Chinstrap penguins bill length is greater than an Adelie penguins, and a Gentoo penguins flipper length is greater than both Adelie and Chinstrap penguins, according to the sample.

For the subset of penguins, there is a weak relationship between bill and flipper lengths within each species. For both Adelie and Gentoo species, as the bill length increases, the flipper length barley tends to increase, if it changes at all. This lack of a visible relationship could be due to the loss of information while subsetting the data based on species, island origin, body mass, etc. Although the fact that the flipper length for the Gentoo species being greater than the Adelie species, on average, is visible with the subsetted scatterplot, we lose a visible relationship between the variables bill length and flipper length within the species. However, there IS a visible positive linear relationship overall for bill and flipper lengths in the subsetted graph.
